import json

def format_blog(id, content):
    if id == 1:
        return """<p class="drop-cap">She woke up one morning and her world changed — but no one had told her it would.</p>
<p>For millions of girls across the world, the first period arrives without warning, without explanation, and without comfort. No one sat them down. No one said <em>this is normal, this is healthy, this is yours.</em> Instead, they felt fear. Some thought they were dying. Some hid in bathrooms for hours. Some never told anyone at all.</p>
<blockquote>Menstrual education is not an optional extra — it is a foundation.</blockquote>
<p>A single honest conversation before menarche can transform a frightening, isolating moment into one of understanding and confidence. Research consistently shows that girls who receive information before their first period experience significantly less shame, less fear, and less disruption to their daily lives.</p>
<p>Yet across homes and schools worldwide, that conversation never happens. The chapter gets skipped. The question goes unanswered. The silence is passed from one generation to the next like an inheritance no one chose.</p>
<p><strong>Girls deserve better than that.</strong> They deserve truth before they need it, language before they are confused by it, and support before they are afraid. Preparation is not a privilege. It is a right.</p>"""
    elif id == 2:
        return """<p class="drop-cap">In classrooms across South Asia, Sub-Saharan Africa, Latin America, and even in wealthy nations, teachers skip the chapter on reproductive health.</p>
<p>At home, mothers whisper warnings in private moments. Fathers are never part of the conversation at all. And girls absorb the loudest lesson of all — <em>your body is something to be hidden, managed quietly, and never discussed.</em></p>
<blockquote>Menstrual stigma is not simply embarrassment. It is a system, and it is everywhere.</blockquote>
<p>It lives in the gaps of school curricula, in the coded language families use instead of correct words, in the ridicule a girl faces when a stain is spotted, in the shame that keeps her from asking for help. Month after month, the message is reinforced: you are less, and this part of you is shameful.</p>
<p>The consequences are not abstract:</p>
<ul>
<li>Girls miss school.</li>
<li>They avoid seeking medical help.</li>
<li>They carry the weight of that shame well into adulthood, affecting how they see themselves and how they raise their own daughters.</li>
</ul>
<p>Breaking the silence does not require a revolution. It requires a teacher who teaches without flinching, a parent who speaks before they are asked, and a community that actively chooses dignity over shame. That choice is available to all of us, right now.</p>"""
    elif id == 3:
        return """<p class="drop-cap">In many low-income communities around the world, a single packet of sanitary pads costs the equivalent of a full day's wages.</p>
<p>For families already living at the margins, this is not a small inconvenience — it is an impossible choice. Food or hygiene. Dignity or survival.</p>
<p>So girls improvise. They use rags, newspaper, torn cloth, leaves, or ash. They wear a single pad for twelve hours or more because they cannot afford a replacement. They sit still in class, afraid to move. And when the anxiety becomes too great, they simply do not go to school.</p>
<blockquote>Period poverty is real, it is global, and it is entirely preventable.</blockquote>
<p>It is not a natural condition — it is the result of policy choices:</p>
<ul>
<li>Choices to tax menstrual products as luxury goods.</li>
<li>Choices to exclude them from social safety nets.</li>
<li>Choices to treat menstrual health as a private matter rather than a public responsibility.</li>
</ul>
<p>When Scotland passed legislation making period products free and universally accessible in schools, absenteeism dropped and reported wellbeing improved. The evidence is not complicated. When girls have what they need, they show up — for school, for life, for themselves. The question has never been whether we can solve this. It is whether we choose to.</p>"""
    elif id == 4:
        return """<p class="drop-cap">Through fieldwork in government schools across West Bengal and Odisha, a pattern emerged that was quietly devastating.</p>
<p>The sanitary pads had been procured. The distribution programme was in place. Officials could point to the numbers — products delivered, boxes ticked, scheme declared successful.</p>
<p>But when we looked closer, we found that many girls were not coming forward to collect them. Not because the products weren't there. Not because they didn't need them. But because they were too ashamed to be seen taking one.</p>
<blockquote>To be seen walking up. To be seen accepting. To have anyone know.</blockquote>
<p>This is the gap that no supply chain, no government scheme, and no distribution network can fix on its own. Physical availability is not the same as genuine access. A pad sitting in a storeroom that a girl is too humiliated to collect has helped no one.</p>
<p>Until we address the shame, the stigma, and the deep-rooted silence that keeps girls from simply raising their hand — products alone will never be enough.</p>
<p><strong>Real access means a girl who feels safe enough, confident enough, and respected enough to come forward without fear.</strong> That is the work that remains. And it begins with us.</p>"""
    elif id == 5:
        return """<p class="drop-cap">For many girls, the hardest part of school is not mathematics, examinations, or homework. It is finding a toilet that feels safe.</p>
<p>Across low-income communities around the world, inadequate school sanitation quietly shapes the educational experiences of millions of menstruating students. A missing lock, a broken water tap, or the absence of a disposal bin may seem minor from the outside — but for a girl managing her period, these conditions can determine whether she attends school at all.</p>
<p>In countless schools, girls wait for hours to change a pad because there is no private space. Some avoid drinking water entirely to reduce the need to use the toilet. Others miss classes every month because the fear of staining their uniform feels unbearable.</p>
<blockquote>Research consistently shows that poor WASH infrastructure is directly linked to menstrual absenteeism.</blockquote>
<p>And the burden is deeply unequal. In many rural schools, boys can continue their day uninterrupted while girls navigate anxiety, discomfort, and shame in silence. The message becomes painfully clear: school systems were not designed with menstruating students in mind.</p>
<h3>A functioning menstrual-friendly school environment includes:</h3>
<ul>
<li>Private toilets with working locks</li>
<li>Access to clean water and soap</li>
<li>Disposal bins for sanitary products</li>
<li>Emergency menstrual supplies</li>
<li>Teachers trained to respond without embarrassment</li>
</ul>
<p>Because when girls no longer have to spend the school day worrying about where to change a pad, they gain the freedom to focus on learning.</p>
<p><strong>School toilets are not a side issue in menstrual health. They are part of the foundation.</strong></p>"""
    elif id == 6:
        return """<p class="drop-cap">When a young girl says her period pain is unbearable, the response she often hears is: <em>“Everyone goes through it.”</em></p>
<p>For generations, severe menstrual pain has been normalised to the point that millions of girls grow up believing suffering is simply part of being female. But many of those girls are not experiencing “normal” periods.</p>
<p>They may be living with undiagnosed conditions such as endometriosis, polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS), adenomyosis, or severe dysmenorrhea.</p>
<blockquote>Because menstruation is rarely discussed openly, many adolescents do not know what healthy menstrual symptoms actually look like.</blockquote>
<p>Pain that causes vomiting, fainting, school absence, or inability to function is often dismissed — by families, schools, and sometimes even healthcare systems. The consequences accumulate quietly. A student who repeatedly misses classes due to severe pain may fall behind academically. A young woman who avoids seeking care because she fears embarrassment may continue suffering for years.</p>
<h3>One of the most powerful public health interventions is simply teaching girls what is and is not normal. That includes explaining:</h3>
<ul>
<li>When cramps require medical attention</li>
<li>Symptoms of common menstrual disorders</li>
<li>The importance of tracking cycles</li>
<li>How to seek reproductive healthcare safely</li>
<li>That debilitating pain is not something to silently endure</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Periods are normal. Severe suffering should not be.</strong></p>"""
    elif id == 7:
        return """<p class="drop-cap">Most conversations about menstruation focus on products, hygiene, or school attendance. Far fewer talk about the emotional burden.</p>
<p>Yet for many girls, menstruation becomes their first experience of shame connected to their own body. A whispered warning from an adult. A teacher skipping the reproductive health chapter. A classmate laughing at a visible stain. These moments may appear small, but together they shape how girls understand themselves.</p>
<blockquote>Psychologists recognise that menstrual stigma has measurable mental health effects. Girls who experience shame report higher levels of anxiety, social withdrawal, and negative body image.</blockquote>
<p>The pressure to hide menstruation creates chronic stress. Many girls constantly monitor their uniforms for stains, avoid participating in sports, or stay silent even when they need help. The emotional energy required to conceal a normal biological process can become exhausting.</p>
<h3>Creating emotionally safe environments requires:</h3>
<ul>
<li>Open conversations at home</li>
<li>Accurate school-based education</li>
<li>Teachers who respond without shame</li>
<li>Media representation that normalises periods</li>
<li>Including boys in menstrual education</li>
</ul>
<p>When girls learn that menstruation is healthy, ordinary, and nothing to hide, the psychological impact is profound. Confidence grows. Participation grows. Self-worth grows.</p>
<p><strong>Sometimes the most important intervention is not a product or policy. It is removing the shame.</strong></p>"""
    elif id in [8, 9]:
        return """<p class="drop-cap">For decades, disposable sanitary pads have dominated conversations about menstrual health. But in many low-income and rural communities, they are not always the most practical solution.</p>
<p>A packet of pads must be repurchased every month. Supply chains are often unreliable. Waste disposal systems may not exist. And for families already struggling financially, recurring product costs become impossible to sustain.</p>
<p>This is why reusable menstrual products are gaining global attention. Reusable cloth pads and menstrual cups are increasingly being recognised not only as environmentally sustainable alternatives, but as long-term public health solutions.</p>
<ul>
<li>A single menstrual cup can last up to ten years.</li>
<li>Reusable cloth pads can dramatically reduce monthly costs.</li>
<li>For girls living in remote areas where shops rarely stock sanitary products, these options provide consistency and independence.</li>
</ul>
<blockquote>The goal is not to promote one “perfect” menstrual product. The goal is choice.</blockquote>
<p>But successful implementation depends on more than distribution. <strong>Education matters.</strong> Girls need clear information about:</p>
<ul>
<li>How reusable products work</li>
<li>Cleaning and hygiene practices</li>
<li>Safe storage</li>
<li>Cultural myths and misconceptions</li>
<li>Access to clean water and sanitation</li>
</ul>
<p>Without education and infrastructure, even the best products can fail. Community acceptance also matters. In some regions, misinformation around menstrual cups and virginity has slowed adoption. In others, girls fear ridicule if reusable products are visible while drying.</p>
<p>Every girl deserves access to a menstrual solution that is safe, affordable, dignified, and sustainable for her own environment. And for millions of women and girls worldwide, reusable products are becoming part of that future.</p>"""
    return content

with open('data/blog.json', 'r', encoding='utf-8') as f:
    blogs = json.load(f)

for blog in blogs:
    blog['content'] = format_blog(blog['id'], blog.get('content', ''))

with open('data/blog.json', 'w', encoding='utf-8') as f:
    json.dump(blogs, f, indent=2, ensure_ascii=False)
print("Updated blog contents with HTML formatting.")
